segments.text: I'm interviewing Dr. Donald McDonald, head of the Department of Civil Engineering.
Today's date is July 22, 1981.
Dr. McDonald, would you please tell us something about your boyhood years in Montgomery, Alabama?
I grew up in Montgomery until I went to college.
except for about three years that we lived in South Georgia in a couple of small towns there.
My father was in the cottonseed oil business, and he was transferred to Georgia, and then we moved back later on.
I went to the public schools there, mostly in Montgomery.
During the war, my father was...
I worked for a construction firm at Oak Ridge, and so he was away quite a good bit, and then moved back to Montgomery after the war was over.
I continued there, living there until I graduated from high school, and then went to Auburn.
When did you graduate from high school?
Went on to Auburn and took civil engineering there.
graduated in May 1952 with a Bachelor of Civil Engineering degree.
How did you develop an interest in engineering?
It was most probably, there were several reasons.

One is Auburn was a real strong engineering school and I had no real driving urge to be an engineer but I knew that was a good field and so I thought I would, I was considering that for quite a number of years but
I had summertime jobs working with the city, the city engineer in Montgomery, and was assigned to a surveying crew.
And over a period of several summers, I worked in various positions on a surveying crew, starting as a rodman and a chainman and instrument man and those things.
And so I became very familiar with surveying.
And like so many people,
I thought that that was what civil engineering was, and it was kind of fun.
I enjoyed it.
Of course, I found out that civil engineering is a lot broader than that as I got into it, but I don't regret that.
It's just that I got in sort of the back door.
I think a lot of people do that.
How was your family affected by the Depression?
Do you remember anything about that?
I don't have all that.
depression baggage hanging over me.
I was born in 1930.
And of course, we went into the Depression or were just going into the Depression right then.
But I always remember we had a house and lived a relatively comfortable life.
We were not wealthy by any means.
My father was a salary employee.
But he was never out of work.
And my mother did not work at that time and didn't have to.
So I really don't have any recollections of that.
I guess when we moved to Georgia, that might have been part of the job scene.
I really don't remember.
But I didn't come out of that with any terrible memories by any means.
What about brothers and sisters?
I have one brother who lives in Montgomery.
He's a little bit older than I am.
He's an investment banker there.
He's lived there all his life except for college and the service.
After you completed your bachelor's at Auburn, what did you do then?
I was in ROTC at Auburn.
And in 1952, the Korean War was going on.
So everyone who got a commission in the ROTC had to go to
the service, so I went to the Air Force and spent three or four months in this country.

I went in August of 52 and spent some time at Fort Benning, Georgia and Langley Field, Virginia, and then was sent to Korea in, I believe it was April of 53, in early 1953, and was there for one year.
Came back, and then when I got back, I was discharged after 20 months.
In this interim, the Korean War, the truce, I guess, was signed.
So all of a sudden, they had a need for no, certainly a less need for people in my category, so they mustered out a bunch of us.
And I went to work for the highway department in Montgomery and spent another year and a half or so there.
When did you go to work for the highway department?
Just after I got out of the service.
It must have been the summer of 53 or 54, I guess.
Summer of 54.
And how long did you hold that position?
Well, I stayed there.
I was what was called a bridge design engineer and so I worked on designing bridges and enjoyed it for about six months and then found out I was repeating myself
lost its interest.
So I decided to go back to graduate school.
And so I worked until the fall of 1955.
And in the meantime, of course, I'd applied for graduate school and been accepted.
And so I went to graduate school in September of 55.
Where?
University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign.
And you completed your master's work there?
Yes, in 1957 and PhD in 1959.
What was the topic of your dissertation?
The topic was a numerical study of the vibrations of spherical shells.
The motivation was the behavior of shell structures under dynamic loading, such as blasts, and primarily blasts that were sponsored by the Air Force, earthquakes, any sort of dynamic load
that might strike a structure.
And the particular structures I was interested in was spherical shells.
So I did a computer study of the vibration characteristics and then did a little bit on what happens if a particular kind of blast pulse impacts on a spherical structure.
It was one of the earlier digital computer studies of structures.
This was when the computer business was just beginning.
And Illinois had a homemade computer that was one of the pioneers.
Not the pioneer, obviously, but one of the earlier of this kind of computer.
So I did use that to do the calculations for my thesis.
What about your family?
I married.
I have three children.
When did you marry?

And I have three children, a boy who will be a freshman at the University of Texas next fall in September, a girl who will be a senior at Bryan High in September, and a 12-year-old who will be in the seventh grade at St. Michael's Academy.
Where is your wife originally from?
She's from California, Southern California.
After you got your doctorate in 1959, what did you do then?
and went to work for Lockheed Aircraft Corporation in Sunnyvale, California.

They were just beginning, well, they were in the early stages of getting the missile and space satellite business, and I went to work in the space satellite part of what later became the Lockheed Missiles and Space Company.
It's in, as I say, in Sunnyvale, which now is called Silicon Valley as well, that
activities going on in microcomputer chips and that kind of thing.
That of course was not, that wasn't even on the horizon I don't think at that time.
I worked in structural dynamics for them and stayed there three years.
That's where I met my wife and we were married as I say in 1960.
When I was there I lived in Saratoga which is a small, was at the time a small community
just on the outskirts of San Jose.
Of course, the whole place has been paved now.
The whole valley is completely changed.
In 1962, you left Lockheed.
Where did you go then?
Went to Raleigh, North Carolina.
I got a job as an assistant professor at North Carolina State in civil engineering.
And so we moved to Raleigh in August of 62, and I started teaching.
in September.
And how long did you hold that position?
I was assistant professor until, I believe it was three years, and then was promoted to associate professor, and stayed there two more years, and then left NC State.
And I got tenure and all that, and I got promoted.
Well, those two things were simultaneous, tenure and promotion.
So I left in 67 and went back to work for Lockheed again, but this time as a department manager at a research center in Huntsville, Alabama.
They were working with NASA in the space program primarily.
And I was the manager of the structures department there.
And you stayed there from 67 to when?
Till 72.
Well, late 72.
become a little bit disenchanted with industry.
And Lockheed wanted to transfer me back to California, and I didn't want to do that, nor did my family want to move back there.
And I had thought perhaps the educational game was where I would be anyhow.
I had met the department head, Dr. Sampson was department head at that time, and I knew him from professional activities, professional organizations.
So I called him to see what the
seen in academia was.
And so that initial call led to my coming down here.
And you came here in 1973?
Yeah, January 1973.
As an instructor, I mean as a professor in civil engineering?
Yes.
Okay, and how long were you a professor of civil engineering?
Well, I still am, so eight and a half years, I guess.
You became department head in 1979?
Yes, August the 1st was when I started.
What are some of your duties here as department head?
Well, I guess it's like any other department head to administer the affairs of the department, the fiscal and the personnel and the academic program.
Obviously, any department, particularly one this size, one can't do that alone and shouldn't do that, shouldn't try to do that.
But I'm responsible for coordinating all of those activities in the department, reporting to the dean of engineering.
About how many faculty members are there in the civil engineering department?
We have several, 65 to 70.
I forget the specific number of people who are in either tenure track or tenured positions, assistant professor and above.
In addition to those, we have
have something like a dozen or so people in lecturer positions.

Totally, though, each of the two major semesters will have something like 100 people involved in the teaching program if you add in teaching assistants and then the lecturers into the regular faculty.
Oh, well, I shouldn't say it that way.
Teaching assistants into the faculty.
Certainly, I did not mean to exclude lecturers from faculty.
What are some of the schools that these faculty members are from?
We have them from all over.
We have several, of course, from A&M.
I'd say a fairly large number from A&M, but we have people from the University of Illinois, the University of California at Berkeley, University of Texas, Texas Tech, just about
Well, I won't say all over, but certainly representative throughout the country.
Probably those I named, I would say the preponderance of people with advanced degrees got them in those schools.
But certainly there are a lot of them.
Are faculty members expected to devote time between research and teaching?
Yes, most of the faculty in the department are involved in one way or another in the research program.
Could you explain more about the research program?
The faculty members in the CE department work in every conceivable field almost in research.
and what is generally called civil engineering, and some things which are not normally considered to be classical civil engineering.
Most of our research is administered in either the Texas Engineering Experiment Station or the Texas Transportation Institute.
In fact, the faculty members will hold a joint appointment with those two state agencies, as well as an appointment as, say, a professor or whatever.
with the university in the civil engineering department.
We like to encourage the faculty to do research and also to publish the results of their research.
We feel that that's just one more service in teaching that we have, one more function that we should perform.
It's involved and intimately involved with our teaching, actually, particularly with the graduate teaching program.
Could you discuss specifically some of the research projects that are underway now or have been completed in the last several years?

Well, that would take all day, but one of the larger projects and one of the important ones, I think, is an environmental impact of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve that our Environmental Engineering Division is involved in.
The Strategic Petroleum Reserve is a program by the federal government to store large quantities of petroleum oil in very large salt domes.
Salt domes are subterranean, and they're extremely stable.
Well, to put the oil in, you have to pump the brine out.
And so what the government will be doing is depositing
high concentrations of brine in the Gulf of Mexico as the oil displaces the brine from the dome.
The government obviously wanted to know what the environmental impact of that large slug of brine would be.
So we're really program managers of a multidisciplinary program involving scientists and oceanographers and biologists as well as engineers.
instrumenting and monitoring the impact of this brine.
Another program is a program with the Air Force.
The Air Force is interested in people who, well, in two things, in developing the general field of the use of composite materials and also in educating engineers who are
knowledgeable in design and use of composite materials.

So we have a program sponsored by the Air Force that's both education and teaching, and a classroom education, that kind of education as opposed to research, in which the faculty carry out a research program in the use and manufacturing, design, and so on, of composite materials.
And I also conduct a degree program so that people with BS degrees in engineering

can come here, study for a year, and get master's degrees in some field of engineering, but with the emphasis on the design and use of composite materials so they can now return to the aircraft industry and apply these newly discovered skills to the use of composite.
Composite materials are sort of, in one sense, the wave of the future in structural design in certain applications because of a very high
strength to weight ratio.
And naturally, if you can have something very strong that doesn't weigh very much, then the aircraft people are interested in it.
But now, of course, there's more and more interest in the automotive industry and the application of composites.
Because if you save a pound of weight in an automobile, that's a certain amount of savings in gasoline that you don't have to spend to push that pound around the road.
Let's see, there are other programs.
We've had programs in the study of the behavior of subsurface, well, the ocean bottom.
It turns out that in certain areas of the Gulf, the ocean bottom is a very uncohesive material.
And due to the wave action in storms,
the wave action can trigger huge slides, mudslides, as it were, on the bottom of the ocean.
Even though the slopes of the ocean bottom are not very large, the material is so uncohesive that it won't stick together, that it'll move under these high pressures.
Naturally, the oil companies or the companies who have that drilling are very interested in that because if the whole floor of the ocean starts moving, there's not a lot that,
Well, it certainly has an impact on the drilling rig, drilling platforms.

So we, in the geotechnical engineering division, have been studying the effect of these mudslides and the forces generated by the mudslides so that we can then take their results and see what the impact on the drilling rigs would be.
And then the next obvious question is what procedures or how can we design the...
drilling rigs to resist these very large forces that are generated by these slides.
You could go on and on.
Basically, this might add a little to this, basically we have, the civil engineering department has six groups, we call them, major areas, major administrative subdivisions.
These are ocean and coastal engineering, environmental engineering,
structures, construction and materials, geotechnical, or I guess we call it geoengineering, and civil systems engineering.
If you look at the details of this, this covers pretty much the broad spectrum of civil engineering activity.
And we have a research program in every one of those areas covering many facets of the business.
Could you explain briefly in layman's terms what a civil engineer does?
The layman's term is not the problem.
The problem is the breadth of the field.
I guess this is very simplistic, but in a sense, civil engineers are the people who design, construct, maintain, and run the machinery of civilization.

By this, I mean all those things, those engineered works that are basic to running the civilization, the transportation network, the water supply, disposing of the waste, constructing the buildings, designing the facility, designing the bridges, designing and supervising construction of the
all the appurtenances and all the buildings that go along with all these things, the sewer plants and such, maintaining all of these, developing new materials.

We have a big program, for example, in the Texas Transportation Institute in the development of asphaltic materials that would be used in highways and other parking lots and other things where they use large volumes of asphalt paving.
Involving all of this, of course, would be the economic studies as to determine the best approach, where to locate the facilities, what's the best way.
And by that, I mean the most, say, cost-effective way to design them and to construct them.
So the economics of the matter, as in all engineering, really, the economics of the matter gets into it very, very heavily.
But there's really no limit.
That's kind of classical civil engineering.
But if you look at where our graduates go, a large percentage, a significant percentage, I don't know the figure, but a significant percentage of our students go to work for the oil companies.
Well, obviously, because here in Texas, that's a very important industry.
And they're hiring people with technical backgrounds.
How many hours does it take to get the bachelor's degree here in civil engineering?
Semester hours?
It takes 146 in our current program.
And how many for the master's and PhD?
It gets a little less rigid.
There's a specified curriculum in the undergraduate program.
I believe it's 16 hours, no more than that.
16 hours of technical electives, but then we have some other electives.
total of about 25 hours of electives.
But it all adds up to 146.
For the master of engineering degree, the minimum is 36 hours.
But there, you look a little more closely at a person's background and interest.
Where does the student want to go when he finishes here?
And what kind of work does he want to get into?
And you might require a few more hours, just depending on
the background, what he's had, and so on.
The master of science degree requires 32 hours, but of course, you have to write a thesis.
We require a thesis for the master of science degree.
The PhD, for the PhD, the graduate college requires a minimum of 96 after the bachelor's degree.
Again, if it's appropriate, we'll require more than that.
That's a minimum requirement.
And of course, a significant maybe 25% or 30% of those hours, depending on the student, would be taken up with this dissertation.
Now, that's about right.
Usually, we'll give maybe 20 credits for the dissertation, 20 semester hours.
But those are only minimum requirements.
And if it's appropriate, we'll go over that.
About how many students are now enrolled in civil engineering here?
Last fall, we had
something like 850, I believe was the figure, undergraduate in civil and 115 undergraduates in the ocean engineering program, which is a degree program in civil engineering department.
And on top of that, 150 graduate students.
All those figures probably don't add up, but it added up to around 1,200 students, undergraduates as well as graduates in both
civil and ocean engineering.
Do you have any women students in civil engineering?
Yes, that's another interesting thing.
I think this is a national observation too, but it seems that that percentage is rising.
We've had on the order of about 12% of our undergraduate student body has been women over the past several years.
That seems to be going up a little bit.
I think with this coming fall enrollment, we'll probably see an increase.
Certainly a trend of increasing the number of the percent of the female, of students that are female.
What about black students in engineering?
We don't have very many.
That's a very difficult problem.
We've had them.
Certainly we would love to have more, but we don't have very many right now.
We do have some.
Why do you think you have so few blacks in engineering?
I don't know.
The only thing, whatever I would say would be just...
opinion.
I don't have any hard data.

I suspect that because of the availability of Prairie View, well, a lot of our students come from the Houston-Harris County area, and proximity of Prairie View to Houston, I would suspect, draws off a number of them.
But that's, if you really want to know the answer to that, I think you'd have to ask somebody who looked into it.
What about foreign students in civil engineering?
We don't have many in the undergraduate program.
We have
So 25% or 30% of our graduate program is foreign students.
That seems also to be rising.
I suspect we could, I'm not sure we could double, but certainly increase significantly the number of foreign students in the graduate program if we would reduce our requirements on the language.
We still try to stick pretty rigidly to a language requirement.

The students who come here from foreign countries, we require them to be reasonably proficient in the language because we don't think it's right to slow down the other students with a large contingent of students in a classroom who are not reasonably good at the language.
Are you talking about foreign students who have difficulty with English?
Yes, yes.
You require foreign languages then for the Ph.D. in civil engineering?
No.
That language requirement was dropped several years before I came here.
So we have no language requirement.
What you're referring to then there is the fact that some farm students have difficulty speaking English.
It's like anyone born in one country learning another language as a foreign language, certainly.
Any one of us would have trouble with winter school in France or wherever.
What are the average salary that a beginning civil engineer with a bachelor's degree can expect?
That's changing so rapidly, it's hard to keep up.
I would say, though, that $20,000 to $25,000 a year would not be unusual at all.
People who go to work for municipalities and some of the other government agencies
might not get as high salaries.
People who go to work for the oil companies who are outstanding students would go above that.
But that's a range, average range.
What about with a PhD in civil engineering?
How much more salary would they expect?
That's so broad that it's almost impossible to answer.
There's not enough data to peg any average figures, but certainly above $30,000 a year.
Do you have any figures or any estimate on what percent of students in the engineering college are in the civil engineering department?
Well, I can pull out some figures in a hurry.
Last fall, there were, let's say, 1,200 students in civil, and there were 10,500 approximately students in the college.
Now, those are not all engineering students.
There are some degree programs in the College of Engineering that are
not engineering, not programs leading to bachelor's degree in engineering.
That's total, the undergraduate and graduate.
So whatever 1,200 is as a percent of 10,000.
So it's about 10%, 11%, something like that.
Probably 12, yeah.
When you came in 1973, do you recall how many civil engineering students there were at that time?
I don't have that.
I mean, I have the number.
I just don't have it right before me.
I would say...
probably in the order total again comparing that 1200 figure on the order of six or 800, something like that.
How does civil engineers compare to other engineers in salary ranges?
That's a changing thing.
And also the impact over the past two years of
The demand for petroleum engineers and chemical engineers have just changed the picture completely.

But two years ago, I would have answered that civil engineers probably run a little behind mechanicals and electricals and petroleum or chemicals, perhaps, but ahead of aerospace and some of the others.
That's changing, and it will probably change.
I know it will change in the future, for example,
if the government goes ahead with the large defense program, that will impact the demand for aerospace engineers.
So the whole thing will change.
Some of the petroleum engineers, the salaries for the graduates of petroleum engineers are something that we would not have dreamed of even two or three years ago.
We're probably average or a little below, though, if you take out all those extreme data points.
I wouldn't say it's enough.
I personally would not think it's enough to impact anyone's career decision.
It's not that significant.
Do you have any idea on how the civil engineering program at Texas A&M ranks with programs at other universities?
No, you see figures on those things and sometimes we appear in the ratings and sometimes we don't.
I'm very skeptical of those.
I guess if A&M's civil engineering department always came in at number one, I'd say they were very accurate.
But nevertheless, it's terribly hard for me to see what those ratings mean.
When you say the best, I don't know what the terms are.
I believe quite often that the way those ratings are made, what they're really relating is the current
gossip among academicians, and also probably more heavily reflective of the graduate program, because that's really where publicity comes quite often.
But the only thing I can say, I guess we have shown up in those, and we've not shown up in others.
But certainly, I personally think we're in the top 20.
But that's, again, a subjective judgment.
What are some of the changes that you've seen since you came here eight years ago, in those eight years?
Regarding what?
Regarding civil engineering.
In the department?
Well, certainly increasing the number of students, increasing the faculty.
We now have been able to attract several young, very, very promising assistant professors.
I think as time goes on, the department will tend to get, and in fact right now, is tending to get a little younger.
Not that we are terribly old in the sense of the faculty department by any means, but there are some people retiring.
And because of the increasing number of students we have, we've had positions and have been able to fill them with younger people.
I think the department is becoming more
oriented towards research, though I'm convinced not to the detriment of our teaching program.
We have not changed there on our feelings of the importance of the undergraduate teaching program.
I think we feel that we can continue to have a strong undergraduate teaching program in spite of a growing and changing, to a certain extent, changing research program.
The facilities have not changed.
That's one of our problems, but there's some light on the horizon as far as our facilities are concerned.
We're getting more office space.
We're going to have available in a couple of years a graduate research laboratory.
I guess I'm telling you what we'd like to see change rather than what I have seen change, but we'd like to see improvement in our undergraduate teaching laboratories, which
We're in very bad shape there.
The curriculum has changed.
The curriculum, as I said earlier, has reached 146 semester hours.
That's gone up over the past.
In fact, that went up just two years ago.
The topics covered in the curriculum have changed.
We think that our curriculum, as far as the topics covered, is probably about as broad and also as modern
as any in the country.
We have not responded to fads so much as other places have.
So the changes, I think, that we've made in the curriculum have been very positive changes.
What are some of the fads that other colleges have changed?
Well, during the post-Sputnik era, so many engineering colleges became colleges of engineering science.

I can't take any credit for resisting that because I was not here but A&M by and large resisted that keeping in mind that engineering is a profession and that engineers are charged with the actual design and implementation not just analysis of various things engineering works and so we have continued to have a very practical bent that is where we want
our graduates to be able to go out, A&M, and actually take responsible charge of the design and construction of engineered works.
Some of the other schools, I believe, became more, also with the advent of computers, became more heavily analytically oriented.
And there are students in some of these places that students really are not prepared to function as engineers, in my judgment.
as well as ours are.
Have you seen a change in the quality of the student entering civil engineering in the last eight years?
I think so.
In fact, I think in even a shorter period of time than that, the quality has gone up.
Now, I could be just reacting or reflecting various scores that I've seen, the average
SAT score, for example, for entering engineering students is now, I believe this is right, is the highest of any of the colleges at A&M.
That's a change from the past several years.
With my own classroom teaching, the students are, I believe, are better as students, reflecting also a national trend, I think.
The students are much more interested in getting
useful and much more pragmatic.
They want to learn things in the classroom where they can see a direct use, a direct application when they get out of here.
I personally think that's something the faculty have to resist.
It's impossible, I think, to identify any practical use with everything that you do.
I think what we have to do is educate them as well as we see fit to be good, broad,
solid practicing engineers.
But the students are, I believe, much more pragmatic than they were several years ago.
But I believe they're better students.
They certainly seem to want to get on with the program, as it were.
Of course, they're always the exception.
Well, that would seem a conflict that general apparent prevailing public opinion that the quality of students is decreasing.
We have pretty high admission standards.
And A&M has high admission standards.
Engineering tends to get those students who, of course, are interested in and thereby probably more proficient than average in technical subjects, mathematics and science and so on.
But I believe that all my colleagues have told me the same thing, at least the ones with whom I've discussed this.
But I think that the quality of students that we're getting in this college and this department is generally tending to increase.
I said one thing about the women students.
The women students, the early women students, again, this is a subjective reaction, were better on average than the men students.
We had some outstanding, and still do, we had outstanding women students.
As more and more women enter the program, though, I think, as you would expect, they seem to be about as good, but not any better or any worse than the average male student.
Many grades and all that would support that.
I don't know.
Again, that's a subjective judgment.
Do you have any figures on what percent of the students who start a program in civil engineering finally finish the master's degree?
No, I don't.
We could get those.
I just don't remember what they are.
We do have a kind of peculiar, what I think is peculiar, anomaly.
Most of the time, when you think of a four-year curriculum, you think, at least I would think normally, that the largest group would be the freshmen.
the next largest the sophomores, and so on down.
That's not the case here.
The largest group we have are the seniors.
We're just almost completely reversed.
Our freshman class tends to be smaller than the sophomore, which tends to be, although there are exceptions, than the junior, and the senior being the largest of them all.
We get a lot of transfers, students who started in other fields of engineering at A&M, and also students who
go to the first two or three years at other colleges and then transfer in.
So the transfers tend to swell our upper division classes as compared to the freshmen.
We don't have a large attrition rate, though, I don't believe.
We lose some, of course, but we don't lose a lot of students to just flunking out.
I mean, with a freshman class in the top quarter of their high school class,
And good SAT scores, you wouldn't expect to lose a big bunch.
Do you have any notion of what that average SAT score is for people in this program?
Not in civil.
In engineering, it was, I believe it was the last fall, it was on the order.
It was between 1050 and 1100.
I forget the figures.
I don't want to quote a wrong figure.
I believe it was around 1070.
I'm just trying to drag that up from my memory, but it was on that order.
I do remember, though, it was the highest of all the colleges A&M.
It was the highest average.
That's on which test?
That's the SAT.
I thought the SAT used a scale of 1 through 30.
No.
They must have changed their scale.
They quote them in, it's an arbitrary scale, but as I remember, 1,000, a total of 1,000, is real close to the 50th percentile.
Could you tell us briefly,
what the future outlook of civil engineers for the 80s would be in your judgment?
I think it looks good.
I think all engineering looks good.

Civil engineering has the trend, the tendency, is for it to follow the population, if nothing else, because as the population expands, we have a greater need for all those things that support the population, transportation and sanitary.
But

Even now, I was told the other day that if you compare new student acceptances for the fall, the first of June figures, compare new student acceptances for the fall with the same figures for last year, we're up 9%.
This kind of just continues the trend that's been going on for years.
We've been growing.
The civil engineering enrollment here has been growing more or less linearly.
with some wiggles in the lines, of course, but more or less linearly for the last decade.
I think that that shows all signs of continuing.
Certainly, the demand for civil engineers is probably going to continue.
Also, the fact that civil engineering here, at least, the civil engineering graduates have a pretty broad education, that is
something that a lot of the major companies want, the major oil companies, for example.
If they can't hire petroleum engineers, they're happy with civils or mechanicals.
And so there's a demand there for civil engineers in what's considered not to be a classical civil engineering field.
So I'd say that the 80s look good.
